{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T02:24:54.719588+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-06T16:41:55.638164+00:00", "id": 13423510, "conceptrecid": "13423509", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13423510", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13423509", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13423510", "metadata": {"title": "Renewable energies and biodiversity: Impact of ground\u2010mounted solar photovoltaic sites on bat activity", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13423510", "publication_date": "2023", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Abstract\n            \n              \n                \n                  Renewable energy is growing at a rapid pace globally but as yet there has been little research on the effects of ground\u2010mounted solar photovoltaic (PV) developments on bats, many species of which are threatened or protected.\n                \n                \n                  We conducted a paired study at 19 ground\u2010mounted solar PV developments in southwest England. We used static detectors to record bat echolocation calls from boundaries (i.e. hedgerows) and central locations (open areas) at fields with solar PV development, and simultaneously at matched sites without solar PV developments (control fields). We used generalised linear mixed\u2010effect models to assess how solar PV developments and boundary habitat affected bat activity and species richness.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    The activity of six of eight species/species groups analysed was negatively affected by solar PV panels, suggesting that loss and/or fragmentation of foraging/commuting habitat is caused by ground\u2010mounted solar PV panels.\n                    Pipistrellus pipistrellus\n                    and\n                    Nyctalus\n                    spp. activity was lower at solar PV sites regardless of the habitat type considered. Negative impacts of solar PV panels at field boundaries were apparent for the activity of\n                    Myotis\n                    spp. and\n                    Eptesicus serotinus\n                    , and in open fields for\n                    Pipistrellus pygmaeus\n                    and\n                    Plecotus\n                    spp.\n                  \n                \n                \n                  Bat species richness was greater along field boundaries compared with open fields, but there was no effect of solar PV panels on species richness.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    Policy implications\n                    : Ground\u2010mounted solar photovoltaic developments have a significant negative effect on bat activity, and should be considered in appropriate planning legislation and policy. Solar photovoltaic developments should be screened in Environmental Impact Assessments for ecological impacts, and appropriate mitigation (e.g. maintaining boundaries, planting vegetation to network with surrounding foraging habitat) and monitoring should be implemented to highlight potential negative effects.\n                  \n                \n              \n            \n          , \n            R\u00e9sum\u00e9\n            \n              \n                \n                  Les \u00e9nergies renouvelables se d\u00e9veloppent \u00e0 un rythme effr\u00e9n\u00e9 dans le monde entier, mais jusqu'\u00e0 pr\u00e9sent, peu de recherches ont \u00e9t\u00e9 men\u00e9es sur les effets des installations photovolta\u00efques au sol sur les chauves\u2010souris, dont de nombreuses esp\u00e8ces sont menac\u00e9es ou prot\u00e9g\u00e9es.\n                \n                \n                  Nous avons mis en place un \u00e9chantillonnage appareill\u00e9 sur 19 parcs photovolta\u00efques au sol dans le sud\u2010ouest de l'Angleterre. Nous avons utilis\u00e9 des d\u00e9tecteurs passifs pour enregistrer les cris d'\u00e9cholocation des chauves\u2010souris au niveau des bordures (ici des haies) et au centre (zones ouvertes) des parcs photovolta\u00efques, et simultan\u00e9ment dans des sites appari\u00e9s sans parcs photovolta\u00efques (sites contr\u00f4les). Nous avons utilis\u00e9 des mod\u00e8les lin\u00e9aires g\u00e9n\u00e9ralis\u00e9s \u00e0 effets mixtes pour \u00e9valuer la fa\u00e7on dont les parcs photovolta\u00efques au sol et le type d'habitat \u00e9chantillonn\u00e9 affectaient l'activit\u00e9 et la richesse des chauves\u2010souris.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    L'activit\u00e9 de six des huit esp\u00e8ces/groupes d'esp\u00e8ces analys\u00e9s diminue au niveau des parcs photovolta\u00efques, sugg\u00e9rant ainsi que les parcs photovolta\u00efques install\u00e9s au sol induisent une perte et/ou la fragmentation de l'habitat de chasse/transit. L'activit\u00e9 de\n                    Pipistrellus pipistrellus\n                    et\n                    Nyctalus\n                    spp. \u00e9tait plus faible au niveau des parcs photovolta\u00efques, quel que soit le type d'habitat consid\u00e9r\u00e9. Les impacts n\u00e9gatifs des parcs photovolta\u00efques \u00e9taient apparents au niveau des bordures de parcelles pour l'activit\u00e9 de\n                    Myotis\n                    spp. et\n                    Eptesicus serotinus\n                    , et au centre des parcelles pour\n                    Pipistrellus pygmaeus\n                    et\n                    Plecotus\n                    spp.\n                  \n                \n                \n                  La richesse en esp\u00e8ces de chauves\u2010souris \u00e9tait plus importante le long des bordures de parcelles qu'au centre des parcelles, mais aucun effet des parcs photovolta\u00efques sur la richesse en chauves\u2010souris n'a \u00e9t\u00e9 trouv\u00e9.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    Implications\n                    : Les installations photovolta\u00efques au sol ont un effet n\u00e9gatif significatif sur l'activit\u00e9 des chauves\u2010souris et doivent \u00eatre prises en compte dans la l\u00e9gislation et la politique d'am\u00e9nagement du territoire. Les projets de parcs photovolta\u00efques doivent \u00eatre examin\u00e9s dans le cadre d'\u00e9tudes d'impact sur l'environnement afin de d\u00e9terminer leur impact \u00e9cologique, et des mesures d'att\u00e9nuation appropri\u00e9es (par exemple, maintien et plantation de haies pour cr\u00e9er un r\u00e9seau \u00e9cologique avec les habitats de chasse environnants) ainsi qu'un suivi doivent \u00eatre mis en \u0153uvre pour mettre en \u00e9vidence les effets n\u00e9gatifs potentiels.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Tinsley, Elizabeth", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Froidevaux, J\u00e9r\u00e9my S. P.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Zseb\u0151k, S\u00e1ndor", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Szabadi, Kriszta Lilla", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Jones, Gareth", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/157c80bc587680264c0da7b38e93f705", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/e3882089ed0929dce1ac3a2d78323b4aaed4ecd83f9b9027f2bd4833423bc202", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/P3INU2VK", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/P3INU2VK", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/9e6564796fc2257df9b9145d97e6c014!/b207055-209613", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class"